 156 -def angle_between_vectors(v0, v1, directed=True, axis=0): 

 157      """Return angle between vectors. 
 158      If directed is False, the input vectors are interpreted as undirected axes, 
 159      i.e. the maximum angle is pi/2. 
 160      >>> a = angle_between_vectors([1, -2, 3], [-1, 2, -3]) 
 161      >>> numpy.allclose(a, math.pi) 
 162      True 
 163      >>> a = angle_between_vectors([1, -2, 3], [-1, 2, -3], directed=False) 
 164      >>> numpy.allclose(a, 0) 
 165      True 
 166      >>> v0 = [[2, 0, 0, 2], [0, 2, 0, 2], [0, 0, 2, 2]] 
 167      >>> v1 = [[3], [0], [0]] 
 168      >>> a = angle_between_vectors(v0, v1) 
 169      >>> numpy.allclose(a, [0, 1.5708, 1.5708, 0.95532]) 
 170      True 
 171      >>> v0 = [[2, 0, 0], [2, 0, 0], [0, 2, 0], [2, 0, 0]] 
 172      >>> v1 = [[0, 3, 0], [0, 0, 3], [0, 0, 3], [3, 3, 3]] 
 173      >>> a = angle_between_vectors(v0, v1, axis=1) 
 174      >>> numpy.allclose(a, [1.5708, 1.5708, 1.5708, 0.95532]) 
 175      True 
 176      """ 
 177      v0 = numpy.array(v0, dtype=numpy.float64, copy=False) 
 178      v1 = numpy.array(v1, dtype=numpy.float64, copy=False) 
 179      dot = numpy.sum(v0 * v1, axis=axis) 
 180      dot /= vector_norm(v0, axis=axis) * vector_norm(v1, axis=axis) 
 181      return numpy.arccos(dot if directed else numpy.fabs(dot))

 183 -def vector_norm(data, axis=None, out=None): 

 184      """Return length, i.e. Euclidean norm, of ndarray along axis. 
 185      >>> v = numpy.random.random(3) 
 186      >>> n = vector_norm(v) 
 187      >>> numpy.allclose(n, numpy.linalg.norm(v)) 
 188      True 
 189      >>> v = numpy.random.rand(6, 5, 3) 
 190      >>> n = vector_norm(v, axis=-1) 
 191      >>> numpy.allclose(n, numpy.sqrt(numpy.sum(v*v, axis=2))) 
 192      True 
 193      >>> n = vector_norm(v, axis=1) 
 194      >>> numpy.allclose(n, numpy.sqrt(numpy.sum(v*v, axis=1))) 
 195      True 
 196      >>> v = numpy.random.rand(5, 4, 3) 
 197      >>> n = numpy.empty((5, 3)) 
 198      >>> vector_norm(v, axis=1, out=n) 
 199      >>> numpy.allclose(n, numpy.sqrt(numpy.sum(v*v, axis=1))) 
 200      True 
 201      >>> vector_norm([]) 
 202      0.0 
 203      >>> vector_norm([1]) 
 204      1.0 
 205      """ 
 206      data = numpy.array(data, dtype=numpy.float64, copy=True) 
 207      if out is None: 
 208          if data.ndim == 1: 
 209              return math.sqrt(numpy.dot(data, data)) 
 210          data *= data 
 211          out = numpy.atleast_1d(numpy.sum(data, axis=axis)) 
 212          numpy.sqrt(out, out) 
 213          return out 
 214      else: 
 215          data *= data 
 216          numpy.sum(data, axis=axis, out=out) 
 217          numpy.sqrt(out, out)

 263 -def rotax( a, b, tau, transpose=1 ): 

 264      """ 
 265      Build 4x4 matrix of clockwise rotation about axis a-->b 
 266      by angle tau (radians). 
 267      a and b are sequences of 3 floats each 
 268      Result is a homogenous 4x4 transformation matrix. 
 269      NOTE: This has been changed by Brian, 8/30/01: rotax now returns 
 270      the rotation matrix, _not_ the transpose. This is to get 
 271      consistency across rotax, mat_to_quat and the classes in 
 272      transformation.py 
 273      when transpose is 1 (default) a C-style rotation matrix is returned 
 274      i.e. to be used is the following way Mx (opposite of OpenGL style which 
 275      is using the FORTRAN style) 
 276      """ 
 277   
 278      assert len(a) == 3 
 279      assert len(b) == 3 
 280      if tau <= -2*pi or tau >= 2*pi: 
 281          tau = tau%(2*pi) 
 282   
 283      ct = cos(tau) 
 284      ct1 = 1.0 - ct 
 285      st = sin(tau) 
 286   
 287      # Compute unit vector v in the direction of a-->b. If a-->b has length 
 288      # zero, assume v = (1,1,1)/sqrt(3). 
 289   
 290      v = [b[0]-a[0], b[1]-a[1], b[2]-a[2]] 
 291      s = v[0]*v[0]+v[1]*v[1]+v[2]*v[2] 
 292      if s > 0.0: 
 293          s = sqrt(s) 
 294          v = [v[0]/s, v[1]/s, v[2]/s] 
 295      else: 
 296          val = sqrt(1.0/3.0) 
 297          v = (val, val, val) 
 298   
 299      rot = N.zeros( (4,4), 'f' ) 
 300      # Compute 3x3 rotation matrix 
 301   
 302      v2 = [v[0]*v[0], v[1]*v[1], v[2]*v[2]] 
 303      v3 = [(1.0-v2[0])*ct, (1.0-v2[1])*ct, (1.0-v2[2])*ct] 
 304      rot[0][0]=v2[0]+v3[0] 
 305      rot[1][1]=v2[1]+v3[1] 
 306      rot[2][2]=v2[2]+v3[2] 
 307      rot[3][3] = 1.0; 
 308   
 309      v2 = [v[0]*st, v[1]*st, v[2]*st] 
 310      rot[1][0]=v[0]*v[1] * ct1-v2[2] 
 311      rot[2][1]=v[1]*v[2] * ct1-v2[0] 
 312      rot[0][2]=v[2]*v[0] * ct1-v2[1] 
 313      rot[0][1]=v[0]*v[1] * ct1+v2[2] 
 314      rot[1][2]=v[1]*v[2] * ct1+v2[0] 
 315      rot[2][0]=v[2]*v[0] * ct1+v2[1] 
 316   
 317      # add translation 
 318      for i in (0,1,2): 
 319          rot[3][i] = a[i] 
 320      for j in (0,1,2): 
 321          rot[3][i] = rot[3][i]-rot[j][i]*a[j] 
 322      rot[i][3]=0.0 
 323   
 324      if transpose: 
 325          return rot 
 326      else: 
 327          return N.transpose(rot)

 332 -def rotVectToVect(vect1, vect2, i=None): 

 333      """returns a 4x4 transformation that will align vect1 with vect2 
 334  vect1 and vect2 can be any vector (non-normalized) 
 335  """ 
 336      v1x, v1y, v1z = vect1 
 337      v2x, v2y, v2z = vect2 
 338       
 339      # normalize input vectors 
 340      norm = 1.0/sqrt(v1x*v1x + v1y*v1y + v1z*v1z ) 
 341      v1x *= norm 
 342      v1y *= norm 
 343      v1z *= norm     
 344      norm = 1.0/sqrt(v2x*v2x + v2y*v2y + v2z*v2z ) 
 345      v2x *= norm 
 346      v2y *= norm 
 347      v2z *= norm 
 348       
 349      # compute cross product and rotation axis 
 350      cx = v1y*v2z - v1z*v2y 
 351      cy = v1z*v2x - v1x*v2z 
 352      cz = v1x*v2y - v1y*v2x 
 353   
 354      # normalize 
 355      nc = sqrt(cx*cx + cy*cy + cz*cz) 
 356      if nc==0.0: 
 357          return [ [1., 0., 0., 0.], 
 358                   [0., 1., 0., 0.], 
 359                   [0., 0., 1., 0.], 
 360                   [0., 0., 0., 1.] ] 
 361   
 362      cx /= nc 
 363      cy /= nc 
 364      cz /= nc 
 365       
 366      # compute angle of rotation 
 367      if nc<0.0: 
 368          if i is not None: 
 369              print ('truncating nc on step:', i, nc) 
 370          nc=0.0 
 371      elif nc>1.0: 
 372          if i is not None: 
 373              print ('truncating nc on step:', i, nc) 
 374          nc=1.0 
 375           
 376      alpha = asin(nc) 
 377      if (v1x*v2x + v1y*v2y + v1z*v2z) < 0.0: 
 378          alpha = pi - alpha 
 379   
 380      # rotate about nc by alpha 
 381      # Compute 3x3 rotation matrix 
 382   
 383      ct = cos(alpha) 
 384      ct1 = 1.0 - ct 
 385      st = sin(alpha) 
 386       
 387      rot = [ [0., 0., 0., 0.], 
 388              [0., 0., 0., 0.], 
 389              [0., 0., 0., 0.], 
 390              [0., 0., 0., 0.] ] 
 391   
 392   
 393      rv2x, rv2y, rv2z = cx*cx, cy*cy, cz*cz 
 394      rv3x, rv3y, rv3z = (1.0-rv2x)*ct, (1.0-rv2y)*ct, (1.0-rv2z)*ct 
 395      rot[0][0] = rv2x + rv3x 
 396      rot[1][1] = rv2y + rv3y 
 397      rot[2][2] = rv2z + rv3z 
 398      rot[3][3] = 1.0; 
 399   
 400      rv4x, rv4y, rv4z = cx*st, cy*st, cz*st 
 401      rot[0][1] = cx * cy * ct1 - rv4z 
 402      rot[1][2] = cy * cz * ct1 - rv4x 
 403      rot[2][0] = cz * cx * ct1 - rv4y 
 404      rot[1][0] = cx * cy * ct1 + rv4z 
 405      rot[2][1] = cy * cz * ct1 + rv4x 
 406      rot[0][2] = cz * cx * ct1 + rv4y 
 407   
 408      return rot

 430          #check if exist first

 469          centers.append(cl) 
 470          radii.append(rl) 
 471          children.append(ch) 
 472   
 473      # we ignore the hierarchy for now 
 474      return rmin, rmax, centers, radii, children

 477 -def ApplyMatrix(coords,mat): 

 478      """ 
 479      Apply the 4x4 transformation matrix to the given list of 3d points. 
 480   
 481      @type  coords: array 
 482      @param coords: the list of point to transform. 
 483      @type  mat: 4x4array 
 484      @param mat: the matrix to apply to the 3d points 
 485   
 486      @rtype:   array 
 487      @return:  the transformed list of 3d points 
 488      """ 
 489   
 490      #4x4matrix" 
 491      mat = numpy.array(mat) 
 492      coords = numpy.array(coords) 
 493      one = numpy.ones( (coords.shape[0], 1), coords.dtype.char ) 
 494      c = numpy.concatenate( (coords, one), 1 ) 
 495      return numpy.dot(c, numpy.transpose(mat))[:, :3]

1773 -    def perturbAxis(self, amplitude): 

1774          # modify axis using gaussian distribution but clamp 
1775          # at amplitutde 
1776          x,y,z = self.principalVector 
1777          stddev = amplitude *.5 
1778          dx = gauss(0., stddev) 
1779          if dx>amplitude: dx = amplitude 
1780          elif dx<-amplitude: dx = -amplitude 
1781          dy = gauss(0., stddev) 
1782          if dy>amplitude: dy = amplitude 
1783          elif dy<-amplitude: dy = -amplitude

8072              ingr = MultiCylindersIngr(**kw)                     
8073          elif kw["Type"]=="SingleCube": 
8074              kw["positions"]=[[[0,0,0],[0,0,0],[0,0,0],]] 
8075              kw["positions2"]=None 
8076              ingr = SingleCubeIngr(**kw)                     
8077          elif kw["Type"]=="Grow": 
8078              ingr = GrowIngrediant(**kw)                     
8079          elif kw["Type"]=="Actine": 
8080              ingr = ActineIngrediant(**kw)        
8081          if "gradient" in kw and kw["gradient"] != "" and kw["gradient"]!= "None": 
8082              ingr.gradient = kw["gradient"]            
8083          return ingr
